S. ambulans

, although having a wide distribution in Europe, has a problematic taxonomy and probably represents a species complex, as suggested by its morphological variability and ecological plasticity (

; 

; 

). It belongs to the crangonyctoid group which is considered one of the most ancient groups of freshwater amphipods (J.L. Barnard & C.M. 

). Its unclear taxonomy and lack of molecular data restrain biogeographical interpretations for this taxon.
